      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That's a good starting point for the literature review. However, for the sake of a comprehensive analysis, I need to look at it from all angles. Some critics of the systemic explanation argue that focusing solely on sociology ignores other variables. From a data-driven perspective, how much do inherent cultural factors or different community norms within these specific racial groups contribute to these statistical differences? I'm trying to understand if there are any non-systemic arguments that scholars frequently debate.",
